  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A put and call option deed is a contract that gives one or both parties the right to buy or sell a property at an agreed price within an agreed timeframe. It is not a contract of sale, and the key distinction matters both legally and practically. If you have been approached by a developer or investor with an offer structured as a put and call option, understanding what you are agreeing to before you sign is essential.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How a put and call option works</h2>
      <p>A put and call option deed contains two separate rights. The call option gives the buyer the right to require the seller to sell the property on the agreed terms within the option period. The put option gives the seller the right to require the buyer to purchase the property on the agreed terms within the option period.</p>

      <p>In practice, the call option is what the buyer values most. It gives them the ability to control the property, for example to arrange finance, obtain development approvals, or on-sell the option, without being immediately committed to the purchase. The put option protects the seller by ensuring the buyer cannot simply walk away if the property suits their purposes but they no longer want to proceed. If the buyer does not exercise their call option by the deadline, the seller can exercise their put option and compel the purchase.</p>

      <p>The option deed sets out the exercise period (how long the buyer has to exercise the call option), the option fee (a payment the buyer makes to the seller in exchange for granting the option), the purchase price, and the terms that will apply when the sale contract is entered into once the option is exercised.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How it differs from a standard contract of sale</h2>
      <p>Under a standard contract of sale, the buyer and seller are both immediately bound to complete the transaction once the contract is signed, subject to any conditions such as finance or building and pest. The sale is essentially agreed from the moment the contract is executed.</p>

      <p>Under an option deed, the buyer is not yet committed to purchasing. They have the right to purchase within the option period, but not the obligation, unless you also have the benefit of a put option. The property is effectively taken off the market for the duration of the option period, but the sale itself has not been agreed. The sale contract is only entered into when and if the option is exercised.</p>

      <p>This distinction has significant implications. During the option period, you cannot sell to another party, even if a better offer comes along. You are bound by the terms of the option deed and the agreed price for its entire duration.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why developers and investors use put and call options</h2>
      <p>The main reasons developers and investors use put and call options are stamp duty deferral and time to arrange finance or approvals. In Queensland, transfer duty (stamp duty) is assessed when the contract of sale is executed, not when the option deed is signed. This means the buyer can control a property for an extended period without incurring the full transfer duty liability upfront. When they exercise the option and the contract is entered into, transfer duty becomes payable.</p>

      <p>The option period also gives the buyer time to investigate the site in detail, lodge development applications, arrange joint venture partners, or arrange finance without the risk of losing the property to a competing buyer. For a developer assembling multiple lots in Brisbane's inner east, for example, an option deed allows them to secure an individual property while continuing to negotiate on adjacent parcels, without committing to settlement until the full site is in hand.</p>

      <p>For sophisticated investors, an option deed also creates the ability to on-sell the option itself, a practice known as assignment of option. Instead of exercising the option and completing the purchase themselves, they sell their right to purchase to a third party for a fee. The original seller often has no visibility of this process until a different entity shows up at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Seller considerations before signing an option deed</h2>
      <p>If you are approached with an option offer, there are several things to understand before you sign. First, the option fee. The buyer pays you an option fee in exchange for the right to control the property. This fee is typically a small percentage of the purchase price, sometimes as little as $1,000 to $5,000, though it can be negotiated higher. If the buyer does not exercise the option, you keep the fee but lose the time the property was off the market.</p>

      <p>Second, the exercise period. This is how long the buyer has to decide whether to proceed. Option periods can range from a few weeks to 12 months or longer on development sites. A long option period means your property is committed to one buyer for an extended time. If the market moves significantly upward during that period, you are locked into the agreed price with no ability to renegotiate or sell to someone else at a higher price.</p>

      <p>Third, the agreed purchase price. Once the option deed is signed, the price is fixed for the entire option period. If comparable properties in your suburb increase in value while the option is running, you will not benefit from that increase. This is one of the most significant risks for a residential seller in a rising market.</p>

      <p>Fourth, whether you have the benefit of the put option. If the deed only contains a call option in favour of the buyer with no corresponding put option for you, you have no mechanism to compel the sale if the buyer simply does not exercise their right. Their option fee is your only compensation. Make sure your solicitor confirms the deed contains a genuine and enforceable put option in your favour before you sign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a put and call option might make sense for a residential seller</h2>
      <p>For most residential sellers in Brisbane's inner east, a standard contract of sale with a normal marketing campaign will produce a better outcome than an option arrangement. A well-run campaign creates competition, and competition produces the best prices. An option deed, by contrast, locks you into a single buyer at a fixed price with no competition.</p>

      <p>There are circumstances where an option can make sense for a seller. If you are holding a development site and a credible developer has made a strong offer but needs time to arrange co-financing or submit a development application, an option with an appropriate fee and a short exercise period can be reasonable. If you are keen to transact but the buyer has legitimate reasons to need time before executing a formal contract, a short-form option can bridge that gap while protecting your interests.</p>

      <p>The critical factor is whether the price is right. Because an option limits your ability to accept better offers during the option period, the agreed price should reflect the true current market value of the property, not a discounted figure the buyer is hoping to lock in before you seek alternative offers. Getting an independent appraisal before entering into an option arrangement is a straightforward step that protects you.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Queensland legal framework and why solicitor review is essential</h2>
      <p>Put and call option deeds are governed by contract law and Queensland's property legislation. They are not a standard form document, and they vary significantly in their terms and protections depending on how they are drafted. Unlike the standard REIQ contract of sale, which has well-understood standard conditions, an option deed can be drafted in ways that heavily favour the buyer.</p>

      <p>Queensland law does not prohibit option arrangements on residential property, but the courts have considered cases where option deeds have been challenged on the basis that they were unconscionable or that the seller did not fully understand what they were signing. The best protection is independent legal advice before you sign, from a solicitor who is not acting for the buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common pitfalls sellers encounter with option arrangements</h2>
      <p>The most common pitfall is agreeing to an option without understanding that the property cannot be marketed to other buyers during the option period. Sellers who sign an option and then continue to receive and respond to enquiries from other interested parties are technically in breach of the option deed and can face legal consequences.</p>

      <p>The second common issue is the option period running out while the buyer takes no action, leaving the seller to restart the sale process from scratch, often months after they expected to have settled. A short option period with a genuine put option in your favour is the appropriate structure to avoid this.</p>

      <p>The third pitfall is assignment. Some option deeds allow the buyer to assign their right to purchase to a third party without requiring your consent. If you agreed to sell to a particular developer on the basis of their plans or their identity, and they assign the option to a different entity, you may end up completing a sale to someone you did not anticipate. Your solicitor should review the assignment provisions carefully and, if appropriate, include a requirement for your consent to any assignment.</p>

